<font color="#FF0000">A THANK YOU</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 30 23:04:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am 26 years old, needless to say, I did not serve in the war, my dad was medically disqualified, he is legally blind and can't see his hand in front of his face without his glasses.  Other than that, both my grandfathers served, one in Korea and one in WWII.  This is unnecessary background, but I wanted to lay a little groundwork for what I am about to write.  <br>
I have always had a fascination with the history, probably because my dad teaches grade school history, and have had an especially avid interest in Vietnam.  Maybe it was Hollywood &quot;glamorization&quot;, movies where soldiers are shown in underground burrows smoking marijuana and singing while stoned, hey like I said, I was young and at the time that was &quot;cool&quot;.  It was later when I read real stories from those that survived the war that my respect for the Vietnam Vet began to take shape.<br>
Yeah, as a kid the soldiers smoking pot was cool, therefore the protesters with the long hair, wild clothes and care free attitude smoking pot was also cool.  These hippies influenced my opinions of the war and I believed that it was a senseless war in an even more senseless country.  I just could not understand why had sent troops to Vietnam.<br>
You grow up, the interest is still there, you read more books and watch less movies, you are introduced to Hanoi Hannah (sp?), protesters who berate, put down and harass the vets coming home from the war.  This began to anger me.  How can you call out &quot;bring the boys home&quot; and when they get there, shout &quot;baby killer&quot; and &quot;murderer&quot; at them.  How can you reap the benefits of a life as a celebrity and turn around and persecute those who served either by enlisting or by being drafted.  The cowards, it seems to me, remained in the states and threw stones half a world away at the very people who had no choice but to fight for their own survival.  <br>
Maybe I'll post more later, but I think it is time to wrap it up, in short, I try, but cannot begin to imagine, being half a world away with a silent enemy sneaking up to me in the form of any person from the age of 5 to 105, walking around a eerily silent jungle, always on alert for landmines, tunnel cave-ins, pits w/ pongi stakes, the physical and mental torture was there, but it had to be all the more disheartening to have the people at home also screaming for your head.  If I may be so bold, I would like to salute all of you who had the courage to serve in Vietnam at the insistence of our government and thank you from everyone who believes that you are the heroes who deserved more respect than a memorial years after the fact can give, you deserved it the day you signed up or were drafted.<br><br>
I continue to have an interest in the Vietnam war and would gladly communicate with anyone who so desires.  My e-mail address I prefer to use is rfluca@juno.com.  <br><br>
To all Vietnam vets, may you always be blessed with peace.<br>

<p><code>-- rfluca@juno.com  (R. Lucas) </code><p>


